{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dcc61550-d425-43f0-9015-82543a0c2c98","content":"For .NET 8 on Windows with admin access, **`dotnet-trace`** is the best first choice — it's lightweight, .NET-aware, and doesn't require installing heavy tools.\n\n### Collect a CPU trace\n\n```powershell\n# Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU profile\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternatives worth knowing\n\n| Tool | When to use it |\n|---|---|\n| **PerfView** | Need OS-level ETW events, GC analysis, or wall-clock investigations |\n| **dotnet-counters** | Quick live triage (`dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>`) before committing to a full trace |\n| **WPR/WPA** | Deep native + managed mixed-mode analysis |\n\n### Quick triage tip\n\nBefore tracing, run `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime` to confirm it's actually user CPU (not GC). If `% Time in GC` is high, add the `gc-verbose` profile: `--profile gc-verbose`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"eba87cae-a3db-452c-b6fa-e1ee9a2ecd7b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I can answer this from knowledge without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":401,"requestId":"AC12:26F840:1362EC8:15CF536:6A06708E"},"id":"dcada76d-8b62-44cb-8265-5ccb01f0a416","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:02:16.957Z","parentId":"477c1544-21bd-484d-87fa-4f4dfaa30e0d"}
